00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.720
Story 1 of Peter Rabbit and other's tales by Beatrix Potter. This is a LibriVox recording,

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:11.040
all LibriVox recordings are in the public domain. For more information or to volunteer,

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:17.680
please visit LibriVox.org. Peter Rabbit and other tales by Beatrix Potter. The tale of Peter

00:00:17.680 --> 00:00:23.120
Rabbit. Once upon a time, there were four little rabbits, and their names were flopsie,

00:00:23.120 --> 00:00:28.160
mopsie, cotton tail, and Peter. They lived with their mother in a sandbank, underneath

00:00:28.160 --> 00:00:33.760
the root of a very big fur tree. "Now my dears," said old Mrs. Rabbit one morning.

00:00:33.760 --> 00:00:38.720
"You may go into the fields or down the lane, but don't go into Mr. McGregor's garden. Your father

00:00:38.720 --> 00:00:44.400
had an accident there. He was put in a pie by Mrs. McGregor." "Now run along and don't get into

00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:50.160
mischief. I am going out." An old Mrs. Rabbit took a basket and her umbrella, and went through the

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:56.000
wood to the bakers. She bought a loaf of brown bread and five current buns. Flopsie,

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:00.480
mopsie, and cotton tail, who were good little bunnies, went down the lane to gather blackberries.

00:01:01.280 --> 00:01:05.840
But Peter, who was very naughty, ran straight away to Mr. McGregor's garden and squeezed under

00:01:05.840 --> 00:01:11.280
the gate. First he ate some lettuces and some French beans, and then he ate some radishes.

00:01:11.920 --> 00:01:14.720
And then, feeling rather sick, he went to look for some parsley.

00:01:15.600 --> 00:01:19.200
But round the end of a cucumber frame, whom should he meet but Mr. McGregor?

00:01:20.240 --> 00:01:24.800
Mr. McGregor was on his hands and knees, planting out young cabbages, but he jumped up and ran

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:31.280
after Peter, waving a rake and calling out, "Stop, thief!" Peter was most dreadfully frightened.

00:01:31.280 --> 00:01:36.080
He rushed all over the garden for he had forgotten the way back to the gate. He lost one of his

00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:41.680
shoes among the cabbages, and the other shoe amongst the potatoes. After losing them he ran on

00:01:41.680 --> 00:01:45.600
four legs and went faster, so that I think he might have got away altogether if he had not

00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:50.400
unfortunately run into a goose-brenette, and got caught by the large buttons on his jacket.

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:56.080
It was a blue jacket with brass buttons, quite new. Peter gave himself up the lost and shed

00:01:56.080 --> 00:02:00.800
big tears, but his solves were overheard by some friendly sparrows, who flew to him in great

00:02:00.800 --> 00:02:06.720
excitement, and implored him to exert himself. Mr. McGregor came up with a sieve, which he intended

00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:11.600
to pop upon the top of Peter, but Peter wriggled out just in time, leaving his jacket behind him,

00:02:12.320 --> 00:02:16.880
and rushed into the tall shed and jumped into a can. It would have been a beautiful thing to hide

00:02:16.880 --> 00:02:22.320
in if it had not had so much water in it. Mr. McGregor was quite sure that Peter was somewhere

00:02:22.320 --> 00:02:27.280
in the tall shed, perhaps he ended underneath a flower pot. He began to turn them over carefully,

00:02:27.280 --> 00:02:34.480
looking under each. Presently Peter sneezed, "Cut your shoe!" Mr. McGregor was after him in no time,

00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:39.520
and tried to put his foot upon Peter, who jumped out of a window, upsetting three plants.

00:02:40.320 --> 00:02:44.960
The window was too small for Mr. McGregor, and he was tired of running after Peter. He went back to

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:51.280
his work. Peter sat down to rest. He was out of breath and trembling with fright, and he had not

00:02:51.280 --> 00:02:57.440
the least idea which way to go. Also, he was very damp with sitting in that can. After a time he

00:02:57.440 --> 00:03:05.120
began to wander about, going lupity, lupity, not very fast, and looking all round. He found a door

00:03:05.120 --> 00:03:09.360
in a wall, but it was locked, and there was no room for a fashionable rabbit to squeeze underneath.

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:14.720
An old mouse was running in and out over the stone doorstep, carrying peas and beans to

00:03:14.720 --> 00:03:19.360
her family in the wood. Peter asked her the way to the gate, but she had such a large

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:24.480
pea in her mouth that she could not answer. She only shook her head at him. Peter began to cry.

00:03:26.240 --> 00:03:30.240
Then he tried to find his way straight across the garden, but he became more and more puzzled.

00:03:30.880 --> 00:03:36.080
Presently he came to a pond when Mr. McGregor filled his watercans. A white cat was staring at some

00:03:36.080 --> 00:03:41.840
goldfish. She sat very, very still, but now and then the tip of her tail twitched as if it were alive.

00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:46.880
Peter thought it best to go away without speaking to her. He had heard about cats from his

00:03:46.880 --> 00:03:52.320
cousin, little Benjamin Bunny. He went back towards the tall shed, but suddenly quite close to

00:03:52.320 --> 00:03:59.360
him, he heard the noise of a hoe, scratch, scratch, scratch, scratch. Peter scouted underneath

00:03:59.360 --> 00:04:04.240
the bushes. But presently, as nothing happened, he came out, and climbed upon a wheelbarrow

00:04:04.240 --> 00:04:09.840
and peeped over. The first thing he saw was Mr. McGregor hoeing onions. His back was turned towards

00:04:09.840 --> 00:04:16.160
Peter, and beyond him was the gate. Peter got down very quietly off the wheelbarrow and started

00:04:16.160 --> 00:04:19.840
running as fast as he could go along a straight walk behind some black current bushes.

00:04:20.880 --> 00:04:25.440
Mr. McGregor caught sight of him at the corner, but Peter did not care. He slipped underneath the

00:04:25.440 --> 00:04:31.120
gate and was safe at last in the wood outside the garden. Mr. McGregor hung up the little jacket

00:04:31.120 --> 00:04:35.920
and the shoes for a scarecrow to frighten the blackbirds. Peter never stopped running or looked

00:04:35.920 --> 00:04:41.200
behind him till he got home to the big fur tree. He was so tired that he flopped down of on the

00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:46.560
nice soft sand on the floor of the rabbit hole and shut his eyes. His mother was busy cooking.

00:04:46.560 --> 00:04:51.200
She wondered what he had done with his clothes. It was the second little jacket and pair of shoes

00:04:51.200 --> 00:04:56.960
that Peter had lost in a fortnight. I am sorry to say that Peter was not very well during the

00:04:56.960 --> 00:05:02.000
evening. His mother put him to bed and made some camera mild tea, and she gave a dose of it to

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:09.520
Peter. One table spoonful to be taken at bedtime. But flopsie, mopsie and cotton tail had red and

00:05:09.520 --> 00:05:17.760
milk in blackberries for supper. End of the tail of Peter Rabbit, recording by Julian Bradley.
